DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3932(82)80004-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393282800044
AB  - This article constructs a unified framework describing the process of liquidity creation in the Eurodollar market. It lays to rest the perceived dichotomy between multiplier and asset substitution approaches to the Eurodollar market by showing the role of each. Views holding the Eurodollar market responsible for a large increase in U.S. net liquidity (an increase in the supply of the medium of exchange or in its velocity) are found to be unjustified. When $1 is shifted from domestic commercial bank time deposits to Eurodollar deposits, about 10¢ is added to the U.S. medium of exchange. Additional effects, such as increased velocity of the existing medium of exchange, are found to be small, even when account is taken of OPEC Eurodepositing.
ER  - 

