UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S030439328280007X
AB  - The potential role for systematic monetary policy to dampen fluctuations around the natural rate is examined in Barro's (1976) model. The source of the non-neutrality is the effect of nonpermanent changes in the money supply on the inflation rate (the real return to money) which induces labor-leisure substitutions. When these non-permanent changes take the form of future reactions to imperfectly perceived current disturbances they affect the deviation from the natural rate.
