DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3932(82)80006-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393282800068
AB  - Since September 1973 the central bank of the Netherlands has applied a system of quotas to formalize the use made of its advance facilities. In this paper we examine some data on the supply and the use made of the quotas and try to discern whether recourse to the central bank is guided by ‘need’ or by ‘profit’. The results provided by a structural regression model favour the latter interpretation of the data, which moreover indicate that the demand for advances react quite strongly to changes in the cost of advances. Implications of this finding for monetary policy are discussed.
ER  - 
